Chidiebube Okeoma, Owerri The Deputy Governor of Imo State, Gerald Irona, has called on the leadership of the National Union of Local Government Employees in the state not to cover up acts of criminality in the local government system in the state, particularly the ghost worker syndrome A statement on Tuesday by his media aide, Walter Duru, said, “Deputy Governor of Imo State, Gerald Irona, has called on the leadership of the National Union of Local Government Employees in the state not to cover up acts of criminality in the local government system in the state, particularly the ghost worker syndrome. “The deputy governor made the call while receiving a delegation of the state leadership of NULGE, who came on a solidarity visit to his office on Tuesday.” “He used the occasion to explain the essence of the ‘Clock-in-Clock-out’ policy of the state government, describing it as aimed at identifying ghost workers within the public service.” He added, “Let me on behalf of the governor assure you that we are committed to reinvigorating and making local government administration more functional and productive. “We will work with the leadership of NULGE to ensure that we move to the next level in our desire to making local governments in Imo work for the people. We need peace in the state and among labour unions. We want vibrant labour organisations that will engage us on governance issues.” Copyright PUNCH.
